1
00:00:01,060 --> 00:00:05,339
Reaching the point of trading consistency
is the ultimate goal of every trader.

2
00:00:05,339 --> 00:00:09,530
And to achieve this milestone, you will need
to incorporate three pillars in your trading,

3
00:00:09,530 --> 00:00:14,340
which will require finding the market direction,
evaluating the strength of the trend and effectively

4
00:00:14,340 --> 00:00:16,290
assessing the volatility.

5
00:00:16,290 --> 00:00:20,400
Most traders apply 3 or 4 indicators to get
this information, but at the same time they

6
00:00:20,400 --> 00:00:22,050
clutter their charts.

7
00:00:22,050 --> 00:00:25,449
One viable solution to this problem is the
Traders Dynamic Index.

8
00:00:25,449 --> 00:00:29,960
In today’s video, we’ll discuss about
the TDI indicator and I will share how to

9
00:00:29,960 --> 00:00:35,580
correctly trade with it and how to incorporate
it in a trading strategy.

10
00:00:35,580 --> 00:00:40,290
Traders Dynamic Index is a hybrid indicator
that can read the market sentiment, market

11
00:00:40,290 --> 00:00:42,970
volatility, and momentum at the same time.

12
00:00:42,970 --> 00:00:47,530
The advantage of combining the qualities of
several indicators into one indicator is what

13
00:00:47,530 --> 00:00:49,780
makes the TDI indicators so special.

14
00:00:49,780 --> 00:00:55,530
The Traders Dynamic Index is based on three
other popular indicators: the RSI, a moving

15
00:00:55,530 --> 00:00:57,600
average and Bollinger Bands.

16
00:00:57,600 --> 00:01:02,250
The standard RSI indicator determines the
strength of the current trend, or if you want,

17
00:01:02,250 --> 00:01:04,030
the rate of change in price.

18
00:01:04,030 --> 00:01:09,920
The moving averages algorithm is used to smooth
the lines and eliminate RSI false signals,

19
00:01:09,920 --> 00:01:15,260
and Bollinger bands are used to estimate the
amplitude of the oscillations, meaning the

20
00:01:15,260 --> 00:01:16,260
volatility.

21
00:01:16,260 --> 00:01:19,600
Now, let’s break down the Traders Dynamic
Index indicator.

22
00:01:19,600 --> 00:01:22,650
As you can see, the TDI has five lines.

23
00:01:22,650 --> 00:01:27,220
The green line represents the RSI indicator
and represents the market sentiment.

24
00:01:27,220 --> 00:01:31,259
It shows you how the market is moving related
to positive and negative expectation.

25
00:01:31,259 --> 00:01:37,069
The red line is simply a moving average of
the green line, meaning a simple moving average

26
00:01:37,069 --> 00:01:42,600
applied on the relative strength index, and
can be used for entries and exits in the market.

27
00:01:42,600 --> 00:01:46,030
The yellow line is what we refer to as the
overall market sentiment.

28
00:01:46,030 --> 00:01:50,619
It’s the middle Bollinger Band and it shows
the overall direction of the market.

29
00:01:50,619 --> 00:01:54,000
The overall market has a tendency to do two
things.

30
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:58,130
It can turn slowly, or it can continue to
go in the initial direction.

31
00:01:58,130 --> 00:02:02,670
This is because the moving average, usually
of 50 period, is less responsive to quick

32
00:02:02,670 --> 00:02:04,840
market changes and turns slowly.

33
00:02:04,840 --> 00:02:09,929
Last but not least, we have two blue lines,
one above and one below.

34
00:02:09,929 --> 00:02:14,599
Those blue lines represent the volatility
in the market, representing the upper and

35
00:02:14,599 --> 00:02:16,370
lower Bollinger Bands.

36
00:02:16,370 --> 00:02:20,480
They are increasing and decreasing in volatility.

37
00:02:20,480 --> 00:02:24,900
Regarding the calculation procedure, you have
several lookback periods you must tweak and

38
00:02:24,900 --> 00:02:25,900
adjust.

39
00:02:25,900 --> 00:02:29,989
The most important thing you must keep in
mind is the fact that TDI indicator is based

40
00:02:29,989 --> 00:02:34,930
on the RSI − all lines of the indicator
are calculated on the information of the main

41
00:02:34,930 --> 00:02:36,430
RSI oscillator.

42
00:02:36,430 --> 00:02:41,041
RSI forms the overall graphic picture, because
the main task is to assess the rate of the

43
00:02:41,041 --> 00:02:42,510
change in the price.

44
00:02:42,510 --> 00:02:48,079
• A shorter RSI period – below 10 - with
be volatile and will have a lower level of

45
00:02:48,079 --> 00:02:49,079
reliability.

46
00:02:49,079 --> 00:02:54,230
• A longer RSI period – above 20 - smooths
out the plotted line and will generate signals

47
00:02:54,230 --> 00:02:57,819
that are more accurate
I personally would not use a lookback period

48
00:02:57,819 --> 00:03:01,110
below 20 on the RSI.

49
00:03:01,110 --> 00:03:04,430
You can also change period of the moving average
applied to the RSI.

50
00:03:04,430 --> 00:03:09,799
I don’t like using fast moving averages,
below 10, so I would backtest moving averages

51
00:03:09,799 --> 00:03:12,689
with 12 or 21 lookback periods.

52
00:03:12,689 --> 00:03:16,250
The Bollinger Bands periods must not be lower
than the moving average period.

53
00:03:16,250 --> 00:03:21,900
If you choose a period of 20 for the moving
average and 20 for the Bollinger Bands, the

54
00:03:21,900 --> 00:03:23,569
two lines will become one.

55
00:03:23,569 --> 00:03:28,439
I prefer to apply a 50 period on the Bollinger
Bands, and in some cases even a period of

56
00:03:28,439 --> 00:03:31,129
100.

57
00:03:31,129 --> 00:03:35,859
So how to trade with Traders Dynamic Index
and what are the main signals offered by TDI

58
00:03:35,859 --> 00:03:36,859
indicator?

59
00:03:36,859 --> 00:03:37,859
1.

60
00:03:37,859 --> 00:03:41,549
First signal: The crossover of the green and
red lines

61
00:03:41,549 --> 00:03:45,680
The short-term trend is determined by the
relative arrangement of the green line in

62
00:03:45,680 --> 00:03:49,861
relation to the red line:
• the trend is considered ascending, when

63
00:03:49,861 --> 00:03:54,889
the green line, representing the RSI, moves
above the red line, the moving average;

64
00:03:54,889 --> 00:04:00,610
• if the green line is below the red line,
the market is considered bearish.

65
00:04:00,610 --> 00:04:02,299
This is practically an entry trigger.

66
00:04:02,299 --> 00:04:07,430
If the green line crosses the signal red line
from below, it is a signal to buy; if it crosses

67
00:04:07,430 --> 00:04:09,969
the red line from above, this is a signal
to sell.

68
00:04:09,969 --> 00:04:14,599
You enter, place the stop loss behind the
nearest swing high/low and you take the profit

69
00:04:14,599 --> 00:04:19,310
at the channel bands (the blue lines) or after
an inversed crossing of the green and red

70
00:04:19,310 --> 00:04:20,310
lines.

71
00:04:20,310 --> 00:04:21,769
Now, very important.

72
00:04:21,769 --> 00:04:26,509
A crossover of the RSI with the moving average
isn’t necessarily an invitation to enter

73
00:04:26,509 --> 00:04:27,509
a trade.

74
00:04:27,509 --> 00:04:32,130
In some instances, if the price trend isn’t
strong, you have multiple crossovers in a

75
00:04:32,130 --> 00:04:35,550
short period of time, offering many false
signals.

76
00:04:35,550 --> 00:04:40,509
Before acting on the crossover of the green
and red lines, examine price action and make

77
00:04:40,509 --> 00:04:45,530
sure you identified all major support and
resistance points on your chart and take signals

78
00:04:45,530 --> 00:04:47,510
from these key areas.

79
00:04:47,510 --> 00:04:53,090
This is very important, take TDI signals from
major key levels on your chart.

80
00:04:53,090 --> 00:05:04,860
Here are several examples of valid trades.

81
00:05:04,860 --> 00:05:14,610
2.

82
00:05:14,610 --> 00:05:19,120
Second signal involves the crossovers between
the red and yellow lines

83
00:05:19,120 --> 00:05:23,930
The yellow line, the middle Bollinger Band,
indicates a long-term trend and most of the

84
00:05:23,930 --> 00:05:28,520
trading time moves in the range between the
levels of 30-70 − with the exception of

85
00:05:28,520 --> 00:05:30,300
speculative moments.

86
00:05:30,300 --> 00:05:33,479
This line will define key turns for a change
in the trend.

87
00:05:33,479 --> 00:05:39,050
If the yellow line, crosses 30 level downwards,
a new swing low could form in the market.

88
00:05:39,050 --> 00:05:44,460
A breakaway of 30 level upwards signals a
potential reversal or the beginning of an

89
00:05:44,460 --> 00:05:46,229
ascending correction.

90
00:05:46,229 --> 00:05:50,490
If the yellow line rises above 70, a new swing
high could form in the market.

91
00:05:50,490 --> 00:05:56,800
A breakaway of this level downwards signals
the beginning of a descending correction.

92
00:05:56,800 --> 00:06:01,840
The global trend is defined by analyzing the
arrangement of the yellow and red lines.

93
00:06:01,840 --> 00:06:05,680
When the yellow line is pointing down and
the red line is below it − the trend is

94
00:06:05,680 --> 00:06:10,720
considered bearish; for a bullish market you
need a mirror image − the yellow line turns

95
00:06:10,720 --> 00:06:13,110
up and the red line moves above it.

96
00:06:13,110 --> 00:06:17,350
Again, you don’t take crossover signals
blindly, you take them after you identified

97
00:06:17,350 --> 00:06:19,380
the key levels in the market.

98
00:06:19,380 --> 00:06:31,090
Here are other examples of valid crossover
trades.

99
00:06:31,090 --> 00:06:40,750
3.

100
00:06:40,750 --> 00:06:44,810
Another signal is the crossing of 50 level
by the yellow line

101
00:06:44,810 --> 00:06:50,811
This trading signal emerges when the middle
Bollinger Band crosses the 50 of the RSI . This

102
00:06:50,811 --> 00:06:55,270
is a long-term trading signal, especially
if it appears on longer timeframes.

103
00:06:55,270 --> 00:06:59,910
If the yellow line crosses the centerline
from below, this is a signal to buy; if it

104
00:06:59,910 --> 00:07:02,700
crosses the level from above, it’s a signal
to sell.

105
00:07:02,700 --> 00:07:08,789
To make the signal more powerful, use it combination
with breakouts of the support/resistance levels

106
00:07:08,789 --> 00:07:12,819
or lines, the formation of new price patterns.

107
00:07:12,819 --> 00:07:17,629
While many trades focus on the fast moving
average, the red line, I prefer to pay extra

108
00:07:17,629 --> 00:07:22,319
attention to the yellow line, to smooth out
the “noise” of shorter-term price fluctuations.

109
00:07:22,319 --> 00:07:27,110
The slope of yellow line is also important
as it indicates the strength of market trends.

110
00:07:27,110 --> 00:07:32,870
When it points upwards, the market sentiment
is bullish, when it points downwards, the

111
00:07:32,870 --> 00:07:34,440
sentiment is bearish.

112
00:07:34,440 --> 00:07:35,490
4.

113
00:07:35,490 --> 00:07:39,870
The 4th signal is related to trend strength
and the range of volatility

114
00:07:39,870 --> 00:07:43,500
The TDI indicator also signals the current
market strength.

115
00:07:43,500 --> 00:07:48,629
We can analyze the relative location of the
blue Bollinger Bands and RSI line:

116
00:07:48,629 --> 00:07:53,680
If the channel bands diverge or expand and
the green line forms a strong direction (up

117
00:07:53,680 --> 00:07:58,770
or down), then there is active volatility
on the market (and the probability of strong

118
00:07:58,770 --> 00:08:02,820
directional movements or continuation of the
current trend is high);

119
00:08:02,820 --> 00:08:07,501
The greater the angle of the green line, the
stronger the players in this direction;

120
00:08:07,501 --> 00:08:12,750
If the channel lines converge or become narrow,
and the RSI line shows short movements − the

121
00:08:12,750 --> 00:08:16,449
market is ranging, or is preparing for this
state;

122
00:08:16,449 --> 00:08:22,060
The closer the green line to the centerline
(level 50), the less the market is active.

123
00:08:22,060 --> 00:08:25,720
So the expansion of the Bollinger bands signals
an increase in volatility.

124
00:08:25,720 --> 00:08:30,910
The narrowing of the lines, on the contrary,
indicates a decrease in volatility and a weakening

125
00:08:30,910 --> 00:08:31,910
market.

126
00:08:31,910 --> 00:08:32,910
5.

127
00:08:32,910 --> 00:08:39,380
5th signal, involves TDI regular divergences
Many trades concentrate on crossovers, they

128
00:08:39,380 --> 00:08:43,940
but neglect an important signal coming from
the TDI: divergences.

129
00:08:43,940 --> 00:08:49,680
Occasionally, price makes a new (higher) high
and TDI fails to do so (the new high on TDI

130
00:08:49,680 --> 00:08:51,930
is lower than the previous high).

131
00:08:51,930 --> 00:08:57,350
Conversely, sometimes price makes new lower
low, but TDI does not get below its previous

132
00:08:57,350 --> 00:08:58,370
low.

133
00:08:58,370 --> 00:09:01,620
These situations are called TDI divergences.

134
00:09:01,620 --> 00:09:06,829
There is a divergence, or mismatch, between
the information we get from price (the market

135
00:09:06,829 --> 00:09:12,580
continues its trend and makes new extreme)
and RSI line of the TDI indicator (the market

136
00:09:12,580 --> 00:09:17,490
fails to break through the previous extreme
and the trend may be changinf soon).

137
00:09:17,490 --> 00:09:23,690
A high probability signal would be a crossover
between the RSI line and the moving average,

138
00:09:23,690 --> 00:09:25,710
after you spot a divergence.

139
00:09:25,710 --> 00:09:30,269
Of course, this must occur at an important
level of support or resistance.

140
00:09:30,269 --> 00:09:41,990
Here are several examples of divergence TDI
trades.

